description.text: This is a sign that says "Memories" with black and white pictures that show through it. It can be used for decoration.

• Type a word in Illustrator, whatever you want the sign to say
  • Make a rectangle around the word (however big you want the sign to be) and change the stroke line of that rectangle to 0.001
  • Click on your word. Make sure there is no fill and only a black stroke line. Make sure that stroke line is 0.001 also.
  • Once the word you typed is selected, go to the "Type" toolbar up top in Illustrator and click "create outlines"
  • Print this on the Epilog Laser cutter using vector cut only. The vector cut settings in the print settings should be like this: 12, 100, 5,000.
  • Once that is printed, print it the same exact way in a clear color.
  • Print a black rectangle of plastic to create a "back" for the object.
  • Get the pictures you want and tape them so they show through the letters.
  • Glue everything together using acrylic glue.

description.text:
This is a braille alphabet which can be used to create words for learning and communicate with blind people.
It can also be stick on a metal notice board by gluing a magnet in the hole on the back.

I designed all the braille plates with Solid Edge, they are simple and all other modeling program can create them.
The braille parts are simple holes and cylinders, the normal text is instead a letter made with Solid Edge in a given
position.

Objectives: The class, but also the teachers, using this alphabet can learn braille and understand how is hard the life for blind people.
Blind students can leave little messages for classmates without disabilities or also other blind students on a metal notice board. Audiences: This Project is suitable for all students, blind or not. There isn't a right age to use this alphabet because I believe it's never too late to learn something like Braille and be sensitized towards people with disabilities. Preparation: Students can use the plates as they come out from the printer or if they prefer to use them as messages on a
notice board, they olny have to glue a small magnet into the hole on the back side.
If the filament's colour is dark student can also paint them for more fun. Steps! 1 - The teacher gives 5 letter plates to each students.
2 - At home the students have to learn the letter, using their finger to "feel" the braille letters shapes.
3 - The day after they have to change their letters with their classmates ones.
4 - Once they have learned all the letters the teacher can divide the classroom in little groups of two students (blind or not) and blindfold all them.
5 - The teacher provide a word to one student for each group.
6 - The student have to find the letters of the word between all the other letter plates and vive them to the other student who have to guess the word. Results: Thanks to the Braille alphabet teachers can perform teamworks engaging also blind students.
This is a good way for blind students to socialize and play with other classmates and to them for understanding how hard life is for blind people.

description.text: Still working on the final details of this thing. The wrist brace needs some tweaking as well as some of the binding posts. All in all the WREX arm does print and function. Binding posts can be replaced with shoulder bolts if desired. Also, The holes should be sized for #10 socket head cap screws. If you scale anything up or down you will need to adjust your screws accordingly. I will update these files as I can. Assembly instructions will be included in the future as well. The Wilmington Robotic EXoskeleton (WREX) Arm is a robotic orthosis designed by Jaeco Orthotics. The original design allows for four degrees of biomechanical motion and uses elastic bands to resist the pull of gravity on the users arm. Two sets of bands independently support the forearm and upper arm. The device was design for individuals with neuromuscular disorders to functionally support daily living tasks such as feeding and writing. More information on the WREX can be found here: http://jaecoorthopedic.com/products/products/WREX%3A-Wilmington-Robotic-EXoskeleton-Arm.html The original design was cumbersome and made of mostly metal parts. Scientists from the Nemours/Alfred I. duPont Hospital for Children created a 3d printed version for children that is lightweight, easily adjustable, and much more cost effective (The original WREX sells for app. $2400). More information of the "Magic Arms" can be found at here: http://www.core77.com/posts/23101/wrex-3d-printed-magic-arms-and-the-future-of-pediatric-prosthetics-23101 We were able to find STL files for the WREX Arm and printed an early model of the 3d printed WREX. The design was fragile and difficult to scale without the source files. This is our version of the WREX. The connectors are customizeable in length to fit all different sizes. This model is designed to be attached to a child's chest brace via the back mount. The left elbow hinges are not my design. They belong to the original design team. As of now, I do not have a version available for the right arm.

description.text: This simple bracket provides a stable platform with which to attach other items to your Makerbot-style MK8 extruder. To install, remove the screws that hold your cold-end fan, heat sink, etc together. Be careful not to lose the four washers that are hiding between your cold-end mounting block and the extruder motor. Remove the two spacers that sit between the fan and heat sink, and put this item in their place. It is sized to be a drop-in replacement. Re-assemble, add whatever accessory to the mounting platform, and if necessary, re-adjust your Z height (bed/nozzle gap). I made it to allow me to securely mount this Thing on my extruder assembly: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1028341 (60mm layer fan duct) Although ABS is recommended when making parts to be attached to/around an extruder, you can probably print this with PLA if desired, as the surrounding parts don't actually get all that hot as long as the extruder fan is running (mine is wired to run continuously as long as the power is turned on). EDIT: 2016-02-24: modified the design to use 45° angles on the sides of the slope, should remove the need for the custom support there. If your slicer can't properly delay the print during the thinnest parts of the print, I recommend adding "sacrificial" objects (e.g. thin cylinders/columns) at the corners of the print bed, slow the printer WAY down to give the upper parts of the print more time to cool, keep your nozzle and bed temperature as low as you can get away with, and point as much airflow at the print as possible (so long as the airflow doesn't distort the filament).

Pay especially close attention to how your slicer handles infill, gap fill, and so on, as this part is easy to over-extrude.

description.text: The model itself is just an example of what the students will be able to make. I chose to design a pen that is able of reusing old or broken pens' refills to work, and therefore helps in not throwing away something that's still useful. It's composed of four printable parts, that will probably need a raft to better stick to the building platform. The pen body is threaded on the inside, so all the other pieces can screw onto it. The body also has a clip to attach the pen to notebooks and papers and the project name engraved on it. The "Pen inside" part is what makes the pen able to use different sized refills. It gets screwed all the way into the pen (with the help of a screwdriver) and has a hole in which the back side of the refill is placed. This part will essentially "resize" the inside of the pen to accommodate all the cartridges so that they will be firmly secured. The cap on the back is purely aesthetic.

Notes: I printed with a relatively slow speed. The whole print doesn't take more than 2 hours anyway. You'll be much safer printing the body in vertical (because of the thread) so the clip must be on the bottom, to prevent tall and difficult rafts and unnecessary stress on the printer.
It's to be noted that since layers are quite small you might need to adjust some settings so that there is a minimum time per layer of ca. 7 seconds before the printer can go to the next level (to let the filament cool down).

Objectives In this classroom project, students will be challenged with the invention of innovative ways of reducing waste in society, on a personal level. Audiences: Students from 14 to 20 years old. The only requirement is that they are able to understand the workings of a CAD-like program. Preparation The students will need to have familiarity with any 3d designing program in order to bring their creations to life. A lesson about pollution and the problem of waste nowadays might help them better understand the scope of the project and the goal of their creations. Steps! The students will be ideally split into groups of three-four people that work well together. They will be asked to find an instance of a recurring situation in which waste is produced needlessly. They will have to find a clever solution to the problem and will be able to 3d print it to test it and put it to use. At first, they will need to make a list of possible solutions to their problem, all together, and discuss wether or not they are good, and why. New ideas will come up until they are satisfied with the result. A session of planning and designing will follow, in which the groups will define precisely the various aspects of their design (shape, size, added functionalities, eventual moving parts...) and will draw sketches of it. The students will then create a 3d model of the object using a program of their choice. The object will be 3d printed and tested and eventual modifications to the design will be made. Finally, the groups will make a report about their experience and present their results in front of the class. Results The lessons will help students understand the working of things that are used everyday, and develop their creativity in finding innovative solutions to waste problems. One example of a project could involve trying to design something to reduce plastic bag usage (for example by providing an easy and portable way of folding and storing them), or replacement parts for objects that are easily broken or lost (such as paperclips, plastic forks and knives) and even find new uses for old CDs and empty plastic bottles. Innovativeness is the key. The focus should be on prevention of pollution and waste and not necessarily on the solutions to the problem, so that the students will understand the importance of small scale contribution and develop their awareness on the problem of pollution.

Esta versión tampoco adjunta el anillo embellecedor exterior, ya que es una pieza muy frágil y de dificil fabricación en 3d, no obstante se puede comprar en plástico inyectado por unos 3 euros y es totalmente compatible con esta versión. La versión V2, está más trabajada (diseño a cargo de mi hermano, que dibuja bastante mejor que yo...) y el reloj puede girar para orientarlo en la posición deseada en cada momento. Por el contrario esta versión no es una réplica exacta, difiere algo en medidas y sobre todo en el ángulo del reloj respecto al salpicadero. Esta versión puede ser buena cuando no va a estár junto con un reloj original ya que no se apreciarían tanto las diferencias. Ambas versiones deben ser trabajadas con lija para quitar el aspecto rugoso. Recordad imprimir en ABS ya que las altas temperaturas que se pueden alcanzar en el interior de un vehículo podrían derretir el PLA. comments.text: A couple things. You could try shrinking the X and Y axis by .5% or 1%. When I printed mine I actually printed it at .3 with 100% infill. It was very very tight and I actually used Pliers to work it quite a bit so it would loosen up. My print quality was pretty horrible back then before I printed a lot of upgrades. If it is being that tight you should really shrink the bolt X and Y by 1% and reprint. The other thing that you might try is pull the parts and thread it while still warm. It seems like the internal threads should be pretty easy to thread if you shrink the bolt. I made the threading pretty large to try and prevent threading issues. It's an M18 Bolt so absolutely worst case you could pick up a course thread M18 and run it through to clean the threading. Or even vice versa with the Bolt. I hope that helps you.

-Place a cube on the workplane, and resize it to 30 mm wide X 55 mm long X 5 mm tall
Step 2:
-Place a cube on the workplane, and resize it to around 10 mm wide X 15 mm long X 4 mm tall. Then move it 5 mm above the workplane, and align it with the first box.
Step 3:
-Place a cylinder hole on the workplane, and resize it to whatever diameter you need more your filament. Rotate it 90 degrees, and move it to the center of your smaller box
Step 4:
-Place a cube hole, and rotate it 45 degrees. Resize it slightly longer than the width of your detangler, and move it into the edge of your detangler.
Step 5:
-Group all objects. Results You should end with a product similar to the product in the photos.

Back in the day when the Beastie Boys dropped their groundbreaking "Paul's Boutique," researcher M. B. Cortie dropped another masterpiece - "Models for Mollusc Shell Shape." In it was described a 16 parameter mathematical model for synthetic seashells, and parameters for many species of molluscs were thoughtfully provided in the appendix. This is one of them. Modeled on the shell of the Turritella communis sea snail, http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turritella_communis, will Purple Pincher hermit crabs like this? Only experimentation will tell! It was created using Maya's shellNode plugin, which is based upon Cortie's model, and thickened using Blender's Solidify modifier http://www.blender.org/development/release-logs/blender-256-beta/solidify-modifier/. The goal is a workflow using open source tools, but this shell surface required a commercial tool. Thanks to a tip from http://www.thingiverse.com/mesheldrake, the conversion to a solid is now handled by an open source tool. :) Cortie's model and many of its resultant shells have been written in Maple http://www.maplesoft.com/applications/view.aspx?SID=3851&view=html. Porting them to Sage is the last step in creating a complete open source workflow. Any takers? Follow Project Shellter progress here: http://projectshellter.com
http://twitter.com/ProjectShellter
http://bit.ly/ProjectShellter
http://bit.ly/ProjectShellterCams
http://bit.ly/ProjectShellterVideos

Some notes:
  • For printing, you only need the turritella.stl file; the other file is just a surface and is provided for thickening experiments
  • Printing with the aperture facing up yields the best quality hollow print so far
  • Once printed, the minimal support material is easily removed and the entire shell is hollow
  • Sanding or tumbling to smooth the surfaces is optional but recommended (more on this later...)
    • You can print it, I know you can! Go!

As usual, I have included the .iges file to facilitate remixing.  Enjoy!

Printer:

Wilson II

Use two 2-1/2 inch 1/4-20 bolts, washers and wingnuts.  (or regular nuts.  it does not matter)

Since I'm moving to San Francisco, I can no longer suspend all of my filament spools above my 3D printer - so I made this very simple accessory to help. This is a no-nonsense single-print filament spool holder that sits atop your printer and allows for quick changing of filament. Since earthquakes are going to be a way of life for me moving forward, I also added screw holes to allow you to affix this to the top of the printer (both countersink and counterbore versions available for download). Think of it as a stability kit. For the rotating spindle axis, you can use whatever dowel is available: PVC, wood or even the original hangers that were screwed in the back of the printer. Have two extruders? Print two of these and place them both atop the printer cover, facing one another, with both filament holes as close to the center as possible. Supports 100mm radius spools with up to 80 mm width (which is all of them, right?) There are many parametric versions of the spindle adapter available, but here's one I find pretty useful because of its cool spiral shape: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1119642 Anyways - I design stuff like this all the time, so feel free to peruse my other publications - who knows what you'll find you can't live without: http://www.thingiverse.com/3E8/designs March 3rd, 2016 update: Added a bigger version for those wide and large spools I didn't know about. :D

â€¢Trace the outer edge of the mirror (excluding the handle) onto a piece of thin plywood (1/4" or 1/8" or 3mm or similar) Cut out with band saw, this will be the backside of the mirror.
â€¢On the backside of the mirror, decorate as desired. Included are some little gee-gaws to print and glue on. See included Picture. â€¢Paint mirror if you don't have metallic plastic to print with. I used a water-based primer first and then a brush on silver paint. (although the silver was done after assembly) â€¢Put 10mm LED into each hole of parts 1-8, hot glue into place.
â€¢Mount Momentary switch into side hole of the handle (part #9)
â€¢Wire up LEDs appropriately. Depending on the batteries and LEDs you use, the resistors will differ. To figure out your resistor needs, use an online LED calculator, like: http://led.linear1.org/led.wiz .
The Channel inside the frame (Parts 1-8) is large enough for the wires and LEDs. It is large enough for CR2032 batteries as well.
â€¢Test all connections!
â€¢Test fit printed parts with plexiglass and back panel. Keep Plexiglass aligned with the inside of the back panel.
â€¢Trace location of Plexiglass onto panel.
â€¢Glue plexiglass to the inside face of panel.
â€¢Glue Back Panel to Frame. (I used Gaffer's tape incase I needed to change batteries during rehearsal/ performance) Enjoy!

I thought I could simply sand a little off the bottom of the door to make it clear the oven bottom when opening.  I did that and then attached the door (using super glue for the one side hinge like instructed).  After that, although the bottom of the door still caught some and took some effort to open all the way, it was OK.  However, my issue now with the door attached is that it will not stay CLOSED all the way.  It opens to about how it looks in your picture with it partially open.  I cannot get it to stay completely closed.  Do you have any suggestions on how to get it to close?  If you think it is caused the fact that I slightly sanded the bottom of the door, I can print another one, but then I'm not sure I will be able to open the door all the way. Naturally, at start of grinding, zero it out.  Subsequent discs will seem to "start over".  That's just the new grit surface holding it up for a few seconds.
If you have an automatic "max hold" feature on your indicator, that makes it extra-awesome!

description.text:
I needed a dust collector for my CNC but I couldn't find one matching my hoover pipe diameter and mounting holes so I decided to design one from scratch. I also uploaded the OpenSCAD model so you can customize it or get inspired, or look at the code. It's not the cleanest code, sorry, but it's better than nothing :) 4xM4 mounting holes on a 50mm square. It's working quite well for the dust but some big chips are still being ejected. I need to design a kind of curtain made with hairs that I will attach under it to catch 100% of the removed material, coming soon...
